 First, we set the two equations equal to each other to find the points of intersection: \begin{align*}
x^4 - 5x^2 - x + 4 &= x^2 - 3x \\
x^4 - 6x^2 + 2x + 4 &= 0 \\
(x - 2)(x + 2)(x^2 - 1) &= 0
\end{align*}The four solutions are $x = 2, -2, 1, -1$. Substituting these $x$-values into $y = x^2 - 3x$, we get the corresponding $y$-coordinates: \begin{align*}
(2, -2), (-2, 10), (1, -2), (-1, 4);
\end{align*}the sum of these is $\boxed{10}$.</think> <answer> 10 </answer>

To solve this, we first need to find the point of intersection of the lines.
\begin{align*}x+2y&=7t+3\\ x-y&=2t-2 .\end{align*}

Solving this system, we obtain \begin{align*}x& = \frac{9t+1}{3},\\ y &= \frac{5t+5}{3}.\end{align*}

Then the points $(x, y)$ form the parametric equations \[\boxed{x=\frac{9t+1}{3} \qquad \text{and} \qquad y=\frac{5t+5}{3} }.\]

The slope of the line is $\boxed{\frac{5}{9}}$.</think> <answer $\boxed{\frac{5}{9}}$</answer>

